To test it correctly:

In /srcs/vscodeIntegration, press F5 and choose Run Extension.
In the new VS Code window, open the real project root, not the extension folder: /home/achaisne/Documents/CCppToolsComplement.
Open a .c or .cpp file.
Run CCppToolsComplement: Generate and Debug Current File from the Command Palette, or click the play icon in the editor title.
Why this matters:

The command is only contributed for C/C++ files, as defined in package.json (line 17).
It does not run automatically on F5; F5 only launches the extension host.
The extension then runs python3 -m srcs.script.generateJson and related modules from the opened workspace, so the workspace must be the project root, not srcs/vscodeIntegration, per frontend/extension.js.
If you want, I can also add a second launch config that opens /home/achaisne/Documents/CCppToolsComplement automatically in the Extension Development Host so testing is one keypress.

---------------

Best architecture:

JS/VS Code side: collect data with showInputBox, showQuickPick, or a WebviewPanel if the form gets bigger.
Python side: keep only validation, source discovery, compiler detection, and JSON writing.
Interface between them: pass structured data to Python as CLI args or one JSON payload.
So the clean replacement is not “move UI to Python”, but:

remove input() from Python,
make Python a non-interactive engine,
build the windows in the VS Code extension.
If you want, I can refactor createLaunch() so the whole “new launch” flow becomes graphical and the Python script becomes pure backend logic.

